Āśramas (āśramadharma) — four, Brahmacarya, gṛhasta, <BR>vānaprastha and bhikṣuka; duties: — Brahmacarya: study <BR>by service to guru and begging food; gṛhasta: the source and <BR>strength of all āśramas; those celibate do penance, sacrifice, <BR>give birth to sons, perform śrāddha, learn the Vedas and give <BR>gifts of food; dārāgni, guests, sacrifice and śrāddha; become <BR>devapitṛs; vānaprastha: bathe in morning and evening and <BR>on ceremonials; eating of fruits and roots, non-theft, purity, <BR>sympathy and non-injury — ten kinds of dharma; Bhikṣu: <BR>daṇḍi, mekhali, and lying in ground floor.1 A reference to <BR>the fifth āśrama;2 will be lost at the end of Kaliyuga when <BR>anarchy prevails.3 1) Bhā. VII. 12. 1-31; 13. 1-10; 14. to the end; M. 141. 61-2; <BR>248. 16; Vā. 8. 177-88; 23. 82; 33. 27; 56. 68; 61. 167; Vi. III. <BR>8. 20; ch. 9 (whole).<BR> 2) Br. II. 16. 15; III. 15. 37-8.<BR> 3) M. 47. 257.<BR>

