Itihāsa (Purāṇa) — Historical literature known to Sūta;1 <BR>the fifth Veda; their origin; to be read or heard on days of <BR>fasting;2 came in a personified form, to see Trivikrama Hari.3 1) Bhā. I. 1. 6; M. 57. 15; 58. 4; 69. 33; 72. 6; 247. 17.<BR> 2) Bhā. I. <BR>4. 20, 22; III. 12. 39; M. 99. 11; Vā. 54. 115; 55. 2; 60. 16; 79. 53; <BR>104. 2; Vi. I. 22. 83; III. 4. 10; V. 1. 38.<BR> 3) Bhā. VIII. 21. 2; Br. I. <BR>1. 171; II. 34. 16; III. 15. 25; IV. 4. 47, 56; 7. 9; Vā. I. 25, 32.<BR>

इद्वत्सर
Idvatsara (I) — see Iḍāvatsara. <BR>Vi. II. 8. 72.

इद्वत्सर
Idvatsara (II) — a name of the moon. <BR>Vā. 50. 183; 56. 20.

इद्वत्सर
Idvatsara (III) — the third year in a five year cycle;1 <BR>Soma according to Purāṇic tradition; he is Prapitāmaha <BR>ensuring prosperity.2 1) Vā. 31. 27.<BR> 2) Br. II. 13. 115, 118, 129; Vā. 31. 55.<BR>

इध्मवाह
Idhmavāha (I) — the son of Dṛḍhacyuta and grandson of <BR>Agastya; a sage who came to see Parīkṣit practising prāyopa- <BR>veśa. <BR>Bhā. IV. 28. 32; I. 19. 9.

इध्मवाह
Idhmavāha (II) — a son of Agastya; and the adopted <BR>son of Kratu; hence Āgastyas are Kratus. <BR>M. 202. 8-9.

