inding two Kāvyas <BR>the asuras became mystified and Kāvya said that he was <BR>Bṛhaspati in disguise; the asuras did not believe in the real <BR>Śukra who left them in anger; soon they found out the <BR>mistake and approached Śukra through Prahlāda and he <BR>became pleased; then he approached Brahmā who said that <BR>after ten yugas and in the Svārociṣa Yuga the asuras would <BR>get back their kingdom; saying this he pointed out to two <BR>disciples Saṇḍa and Marka equal to Bṛhaspati, and at last <BR>the devas were defeated. Seeing the success of the asuras <BR>Viṣnu took different avatars to put them down.4 1) Br. III. 1. 76; 68. 86; 72. 95; 73. 1, 37. Vā. 59. 90; <BR>62. 41; 65. 74-7.<BR> 2) Vi. 70. 4.<BR> 3) Vi. IV. 10. 7.<BR> 4) Vā. 97. 94 to end and ch. 98; Br. III, 72. 96 to the end; 73. <BR>1-64.<BR>

