छाया
Chāyā (I) — a daughter of Viśvakarman,1 a servant<BR>maid of Samjñā engaged by the latter for her husband. Hence <BR>wife of the sun God without his knowledge and mother of <BR>Śanaiścara and Tapatī during the absence of Samjñā as a <BR>horse. Her sons were Śrutaśrava and Śrutakarma or <BR>Sāvarṇi Manu and Saturn respectively; illtreated Samjñā's <BR>children. Yama protested and was cursed to lose his legs. <BR>He reported to his father who said that they would be <BR>restored after some time. Then he asked Chāyā why she <BR>showed difference between her sons and she spoke the <BR>truth. The sun God flew into a rage and demanded <BR>Tvaṣtā to give up his daughter. He showed the place where <BR>Sarvajñā was and Tvaṣtā reduced his tejas. On seeing her, <BR>Śukra came through his nostrils from which were born the <BR>Aśvins or Nāsatya and Dasra.2 1) Bhā. VIII. 13. 8 and 10. M. 11. 5-9; 248. 73; Vā. 84. 39-77.<BR> 2) Br. III. 59. 32-77; IV. 35. 47; Bhā. VI. 6. 41.<BR>

