पुष्पवाहन
Puṣpavāhana — a King of Rathantara Kalpa; Brahmā <BR>was pleased at his tapas and gave him a golden lotus; after <BR>him came the 7th dvīpa, Puṣkaradvīpa (s.v); he got a vehicle <BR>of Puṣpavāhana which took him to any place; his wife was <BR>Lāvaṇyavatī; once he met the sage Prācetas and asked him <BR>the reason for his wealth etc. He said that in the previous <BR>birth he was a hunter and owing to a distressing famine, he <BR>could not get anything to eat; so he plucked some lotus <BR>flowers and went to the Vaidiśa city for selling them; none <BR>offered to buy; soon he heard a musical sound near by; <BR>going in that direction he saw a courtesan engaged in <BR>vibhūtidvādaśi vratam; there, he gave all flowers needed <BR>for the performance of the vow and did not take gold or <BR>food offered in return; he felt no thirst or hunger; and be<BR>came changed at that sight; for that service he became <BR>King and the courtesan Prītī, wife of the Lord of love. <BR>M. 100. 1-32.

पुष्पवाहिनी
Puṣpavāhinī — a R. in Bhāratavarṣa: felt the prowess of <BR>Hiraṇyakaśīpu. <BR>M. 163. 64.

